Interestingly , m-calpain <termsem="GO:0010467"> expression </term> persisted in these cells , suggesting a possible requirement of m-calpain for cell survival [ 30 ] .
Targeted gene deletion in mice provides a powerful approach to determining the physiological roles of  - and m-calpain and the opportunity to approach their isoform specific functions .
Initial studies targeted Capn4 based on the prediction that loss of this calpain subunit would abolish activity of both  - and m-calpain .
Capn4 - / - murine embryos <termsem="GO:0016265"> died </term> between days 10 and 11 of <termsem="GO:0007565"> gestation </term> , and there was no detectable  - or m-calpain activity in these or younger embryos [ 31 ] .
